<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-140-408  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 140 408.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  April 1989 v14 n4 p168(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What is a UPS? (uninterruptible power systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Waller, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An uninterruptible power system (UPS) provides continuous powerwhen the utility supply fails.andP;  It is not a power supply and notevery UPS is truly uninterruptible.andP;  They are more correctlycalled standby power systems (SPSes).andP;  Some designs are actuallyuninterruptible and standby at the same time.andP;  An SPS turns on aninverter when the utility power fails, converting battery powerinto an AC source to keep the microcomputer running.andP;  A true UPSchanges the power to DC and charges the battery.andP;  Energy conductedthrough the DC bus provides power to the inverter, which providespower to the microcomputer.andP;  A full-time AC-to-DC-to-AC conversiontakes place and the system is on-line all of the time.andP;  Featuresthat should be considered in purchasing an SPS include switchingtime, a selectable transfer point, hysteresis (an extension of thetransfer point), and low-battery shutoff.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Power SupplyUninterruptible Power Supply.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The block diagram of a standby power system. (chart)The block diagram of a true on-line UPS. (chart)The block diagram of a ferroresonant UPS. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>